   <abstract>A map of Mexico, California, and Oregon in 1847 created just before the Mexican-American War. In addition to Mexico itself, the map depicts Mexican California (Baja) and Upper California, Texas, British-held Oregon country, and Indian Territory, naming all the tribes removed to that territory. European and American forts and missions are named; major western trails such as the Oregon and Santa Fe are shown. It also provides much detail for Western native tribes, natural features such as mountains, and includes a distances table.</abstract>
   <abstract>""Manifest destiny""(the belief that the country should span from the Atlantic to the Pacific Ocean) is most often associated with the territorial expansion of the United States from 1812 to 1860, including the Mexican-American War, which was being fought as this map was published. President James K. Polk embraced this idea, requested and received a declaration of war against Mexico from Congress, and sent Generals Zachary Taylor and Winfield Scott to lead the invasion.</abstract>
